        { "key": "right", "label": "right", "type": "value" }
      ],
      "visible": true,
      "showLabel": true,
      "data": {
        "markdown": "## What Is Twilite? draft\n\nMost AI work disappears.\n\nIt ends up trapped in chat history, buried in folders, scattered across screenshots, or flattened into documents that hide the relationships that made the idea useful in the first place.\n\nTwilite is an attempt to fix that.\n\nTwilite is a graph-native workspace where ideas, systems, notes, tutorials, products, and workflows can live as persistent nodes with visible relationships, stable addresses, and reusable views.\n\nInstead of asking people and AI to rebuild context over and over again, Twilite gives that context a place to live.\n\nA graph in Twilite is not just a picture. It is an authored information space.\n\nA declaration says what the graph is and what kind of artifact it means to be. Ports expose usable surfaces. Portals move you from one graph to another. And the nodes inside the graph remain inspectable, editable, and linkable instead of collapsing into a dead screenshot or a blob of text.\n\nThat matters because most real work is relational.\n\nProducts relate to launch plans. Tutorials relate to contracts. Tasks relate to evidence, questions, and decisions. And when those things are forced into linear documents or disposable chats, you lose the structure that made them understandable.\n\nTwilite keeps that structure visible.\n\nIt also means humans and AI can work in the same semantic space.\n\nInstead of AI generating output into a vacuum, it can read and write against a graph that already has identity, references, surfaces, and boundaries. That makes collaboration more durable and less dependent on remembering the exact right prompt from three days ago.\n\nThe easiest way to see this is the product page itself.\n\nIn Twilite, the product page is a graph. The tutorial shelf is a graph. The planning work is a graph. Even the launch checklist can be a graph.\n\nThe medium is not separate from the message. The structure is part of the product.\n\nSo if the question is, what is Twilite?\n\nTwilite is a persistent graph workspace for humans and AI.\n\nIt is a place where meaning can keep its relationships.\n\nAnd if that sounds interesting, the next step is simple: bootstrap the LLM, open the tutorials, and start one graph that actually matters to you.",
        "identity": {
          "graphId": "launch-content-declaration"
        }
      }
    },
